Here we can see that there is a stationary pattern emerging from both our instances of positive cases and negative tests, it appears that they are happening consistently during the winter season each year, which makes sense as that time frame typically correlates with flu season each year.

Both Spectral Densities suggest theres a wandering behavior outside of the spikes which are not super apparent visually, but we can see a hint of them at around .15 and .4 on both positive and negative plots.

aic5.wge(flu_tidy$Positive, p = 0:15, q = 0:15)

Next, we will begin to work on finding out which model is going to give us the best fit for forecasting positive cases in the future. Looking at our instances of positive cases, the most favored model with respect to AIC is an AR(7) model which has an AIC score of 14.162, followed by an ARMA (2,7) model with an AIC of 14.6889. Looking down our list, we cant seem to find an instance that achieves a high arma score and uses less than 7 phis and thetas combined, so we will focus on the AR(7) as the ideal.

The positive instances is even more complex with the smallest model having 11 phis and thetas.

Considering, visually, we have a large seasonality associated with our positive tests, so lets see if we can reduce the impact of it.

seasdif = artrans.wge(flu_tidy$Positive, c(rep(0,51),1))

parzen.wge(seasdif)

Accounting for the weekly seasonaility by running differencing on 52 weeks, we can see that we have a smoothe spectral density and a realization that relies less on on the 4 seasonal factors in the winter and shows more of the change in demand year over year.

flufore1 = fore.aruma.wge(flu_tidy$Positive, s = 52, n.ahead = 45, lastn = TRUE)

ase1 = mean(((flufore1$f - flu_tidy$Positive[135:179])))
ase1
## [1] -1788.444
flufore2 = fore.aruma.wge(seasdif, s = 52, n.ahead = 45, lastn = TRUE)

ase2 = mean(((flufore2$f - flu_tidy$Positive[135:179])))
ase2
## [1] -9753.844

Lets try a nueral model.

flu_train = ts(flu_tidy$Positive[1:153], start = c(2017,1),frequency = 52)
nonflu_train = ts(flu_tidy$Negative[1:153], start = c(2017,1),frequency = 52)
flu_test = ts(flu_tidy$Positive[154:179], start = c(2019,49),frequency = 52)
nonflu_test = ts(flu_tidy$Negative[154:179], start = c(2019,49),frequency = 52)
#set.seed(255)
fit.mlp= mlp(flu_train, lags=1:52, hd.auto.type="valid",hd.max=10)
## Warning: The chosen seasonal unit root test encountered an error when testing for the second difference.
## From chol.default(): the leading minor of order 51 is not positive definite
